commentTextOriginal:
I believe in freedom too.  I believe anti-vaxxers should have the right to take their chances with getting sick and even dying if that's the route they want to choose.  However, I also believe that those of us who accept science and mainstream medicine, should not have to pay for their folly.  That means no publicly funded intervention for anti-vaxxers.  No public hospital admissions for anti-vaxxers.  If you refuse the vaccine and get sick folks, well good luck to  you and I hope you have enough money to access private care.  But don't jam up public medical facilities with your infected persons.

We who are pro-vaccine are entitled to freedom too.  And one of those freedoms is the right to access the publicly funded health care we have paid for, without having to fight our way through a mob of infected anti-vaxxers who've suddenly decided -- AFTER they get sick -- that maybe mainstream medicine isn't such a bad idea after all.

Go be free, anti-vaxxers.  But stay out of the way of the rest of us while you're doing it...

I come from Sweden and it's also a choice here. I was one of the hesitant ones. They vaccinated in sections, starting with the elderly first. commentTextOriginal: As Americans, we have a choice. We appreciate our workers who choose to get vaccinated. This is NOT an inoculation and should not be advertised as such. However this video is bordering fear-mongering amongst its viewers. The vaccine should speak for itself. My body my right, period. There are numerous cases of people who are unable to get the “vaccine” due to health reasons, and many who just choose not to do it. And that is there right as citizens of a Free America. And they support your right to get vaccinated. Covid is a real thing. As a nation as a community we all must be very careful and slow the spread. We all must appreciate and value those who chose to be on the frontlines. And my heart goes out to those vaccinated or unvaccinated who have been affected by this virus. I truly believe that with proper testing, proof of no side effects (because the reality is there are many) and once the “vaccine” either becomes an inoculation or is as advertised; as a flu shot to lessen the effects of Covid; I believe that more people will get it. But taking away our right to decide is not how you go about doing that. I see both sides of the argument, but I feel that more often than not people are just concerned about there rights being infringed upon as well as the side effects that this vaccine has caused being that it’s not even an inoculation. We will get there and our nation will get there. The “vaccine” does not lessen your chance of getting it, or spreading it, it just gives you a higher chance of not dying from it. I’m not here to argue just stating the obvious. The vaccine will speak for itself especially if it becomes an well tested inoculation. But everyone has the right to a different opinion, and we should all respect that.

commentTextOriginal: I believe people should have the right to choose to get vaccinated or not. I work in healthcare and volunteered to work before there was even a vaccine in a house that was completely taken over with covid and ended up getting it myself. I have chosen not to get vaccinated. Not because I'm totally against being vaccinated. One I don't think we have enough research on this vaccine. Two I don't like being told I have to do something. And third I think there needs to be some studies on people who have had covid and whether or not they really need to have two shots or just a booster. I don't want to keep putting stuff into my body if I don't need to. If myself and anyone else who has had covid have already built up some natural immunity what's to say that we may only need one booster shot. I would like to see some more studies on people who have had it already and their immune systems. I would like to see how our immune systems have dealt with this naturally and how much of a booster we may actually need before deciding on whether or not I would want to take the vaccine. I believe this is the cause for some people's hesitation. Some countries have proven to people who have already had covid may not need to have two shots but only one booster. I think our country needs to start doing the same thing. I think that would be a good way to maybe start convincing people to reconsider getting vaccinated. Again this is just my opinion you do not have to agree with me.

commentTextOriginal:
The vaccine is not a CURE.  It simply helps reduce the severity of CoVid if one were to get it.
The vaccine does not 'spread' CoVid.
Wearing a mask reduces the risk of spreading to others.
Getting the vaccine reduces the severity of CoVid
By reducing the severity of CoVid, it means one has a greater chance to survive.
It also means it reduces the burden on hospitals and staff and allows to save much needed space/equipment for those who actually need it.

It is a better choice that one has a greater chance to survive an infection, saving heartache for friends/family of one's passing, and saving much needed hospital space/equipment for those in true need.  Getting the vaccine is actually a contribution to your community on the whole.
